<TITLE> Extradition delayed for suspect in Kercher murder </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BERLIN, Nov 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - German authorities are delaying the extradition of a man suspected of being involved in the brutal murder of British student Meredith Kercher until they receive more information from Italy, prosecutors said on Friday. Rudy Hermann Guede, 20, of the Ivory Coast, was arrested Nov. 20 in Germany after being caught on a train near the Rhine River without a valid ticket. Italian police requested Guede's extradition after finding fingerprints matching his on Kercher's pillow. The 21-year-old exchange student from Leeds University was found dead on Nov. 2 in the town of Perugia, semi-naked, with a deep cut to her throat. Germany wants assurances that if Guede is sentenced to life, his case will be reviewed after 20 years, according to a statement issued Friday by the Prosecutor's Office in the state of Rhineland-Palatinate. Italian law provides for a review after only 26 years, according to German prosecutors. Authorities are checking new information from Italy and expect a decision as soon as Monday, said Karl-Rudolf Winkler, a senior prosecutor in the Rhineland-Palatinate office. Kercher's murder has resonated around Europe, where thousands of young people like her study under the Erasmus exchange programme. Prosecutors believe she was killed because she refused to have sex with one or more attacke
